post_text:
Traffic closures will continue next week in Pharr, east McAllen

Closures for the I-2/I-69C Interchange Project will continue next week, Sept. 14-Sept. 18. The following closures will take place from 8 am to 5 pm. Various closures will take place on the I-2 westbound frontage road between Cesar Chavez Road in San Juan and 2nd Street in McAllen. Various closures will take place on the I-69C northbound frontage road between I-2 and Nolana Loop in Pharr.

Nightly closures will be from 9 pm - 5 am. Various single-lane closures will take place on the I-69C southbound frontage road between Sioux Road and I-2 in Pharr. The SH 495 exit ramp will be closed during these hours. Various lane closures will take place on SH 495 between Hibiscus St. and Cypress St. in Pharr. SH 495 will remain open for through-traffic. Drivers are reminded to stay alert and slowdown in roadwork zones, to be aware of lane closures and alternate routes, and to follow all traffic control updates. Have a good weekend.

post_text: Kids, get ready to move. The seventh annual McAllen Kids Marathon Kickoff will be Saturday, September 26, 2020. This year, it will be a virtual event from your own home! It will start at 9 a.m. Go online to McAllen ISD’s Facebook Page and see it live! Then as you log your miles during the fall, you can participate in the Kids Marathon Final Mile on January 16, 2021. Just register at https://buff.ly/3bPdDMV. It’s for kids in kindergarten through eighth grade. It’s free and healthy. Lets move! #DistrictOfChampions City of McAllen TX Government

Traffic closures to continue Sept. 8-11.

Multiple daily and nightly closures will take place Tuesday, Sept. 8, through Friday, Sept. 11, for the I-2/I-69C Interchange Project.

The following daily closures will take place between 8 am-5 pm. Single-lane closures will take place on the I-2 westbound frontage road between Cesar Chavez Road in San Juan and 2nd St. in McAllen.

Single-lane closures will take place on the I-69C northbound frontage road between I-2 and Nolana Loop in Pharr.

Nightly closures will be from 9 pm-5 am. Single-lane closures will take place on I-69C southbound frontage road between Sioux Road and I-2. The SH 495 exit ramp will be closed during these hours. Lane closures will take place on eastbound and westbound SH 495 between Hibiscus St. and Cypress St. in Pharr. SH 495 will remain open for through-traffic.

Drivers are reminded to stay alert and slowdown in roadwork zones, to be aware of lane closures and alternate routes, and to follow all traffic control updates.

post_text: At a joint press conference, McAllen Mayor Jim Darling and McAllen ISD Superintendent Dr. J.A. Gonzalez shared news about improved connectivity in the south part of McAllen. The City has installed 490 Wi Fi units on light poles. This will improve internet connectivity for students and their families which is vital with children currently learning from home. In McAllen ISD, all students have access to either an iPad (elementary grades) or a Chromebook (middle school & high school). For information on registering in McAllen ISD, call the Student Outreach Dept. at 956-687-6473.

post_text:
McAllen ISD’s graduates in the Class of 2020 have set a new district record in scholarship earnings, soaring past $54 million.

McAllen ISD’s graduating class has earned a collective $54,025,316. This surpasses the previous record total by more than $3 million. Last year, McAllen ISD graduates earned $50,733,937 – a difference of $3,291,379.

Some highlights include:

2nd year to reach more than $50 million in scholarships.
5th straight year to surpass $35 million in scholarships.
6-year total of more than $242 million in scholarships.

The students’ awards ranged from $250 to full tuition paid scholarships. McAllen ISD recognized approximately 1,770 diploma-candidates during graduation ceremonies held in early June.

We are so happy to share our meal program will resume on Monday, July 13, from 10:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m.

We know the importance of this resource to our community and appreciate your patience and support as we work to ensure the safety of our program.

We will resume Monday with some changes:
1. Meals will be distributed twice per week on Mondays and Wednesdays. We will distribute bundles for the first half of the week on Monday and the second half of the week on Wednesday.

2. Our meal locations have also changed. Our locations are listed below.

Please reach out if you have any questions. We look forward to seeing you on Monday!

post_text: Students in Ms. Anna Martinez' kindergarten class at McAuliffe Elementary are learning to read, write and speak in two languages thanks to the Dual Language program. We offers Dual Language at seven elementary campuses. Students who wish to continue mastering dual languages can do so at Fossum Middle School. The students have continued their studies during our switch to Distance Learning. Thanks to Distance Learning, they can learn from the safety of their own home. #DistrictOfChampions #DistanceLearning #WeGotThis

post_text:
With our whole world shifted toward distance learning and everyone sheltering-at-home, we thought it would be fun to take a lighthearted look at how our world of learning has transformed.

This song, "Virtually Part of Your World," is a parody of "Part of Your World" from the film The Little Mermaid. Special thanks go to Sean Folk, Theatre Director at Morris MS, who is the producer and arranger of this project; Alissa Shirah, Morris MS Math Teacher, who wrote the lyrics for the parody; and Evie Shirah, McAllen High Choir student who is the vocalist for the track. #DistrictOfChampions #DistanceLearning #WeGotThis

shared_text:
City of McAllen TX Government
April 7 at 5:26 PM ·

Hidalgo County Requires Masks During Stay At Home Order

Effective at 11:59 p.m. on Tuesday, April 7, Hidalgo County is requiring every resident to wear a nose and mouth covering when out in public, if social distancing cannot be maintained, or in a building accessible to the public. Also, note that the order does NOT mandate the use of N95 or medical grade masks for this purpose. Please be advised a scarf, handkerchief, or other cloth mask can be worn. These types of masks will be required to be used as appropriate until this order expires on April 30.

Hidalgo County officials have determined that extraordinary measures are necessary to mitigate the effects of the Novel COVID-19 and slow the spread. Residents are only allowed to leave their homes for essential businesses such as grocery stores, banks, doctor’s visits, outdoor exercise and childcare. For those engaging in outdoor activity, social distancing of 6 feet or more must be practiced.

Please visit https://www.hidalgocounty.us/ to view the order in its entirety.

post_text:
Audra Wright, a senior at Memorial HS, is one of just 26 students across Texas to be awarded a Texas Music Educators Association (TMEA) Scholarship.

Wright is a two-time TMEA All-State Choir member. She will receive a $2,500 scholarship. Only two students in the RGV earned this honor.

“Audra is an amazing musician and will be majoring in music,” McAllen ISD Fine Arts Director Jim Egger said. “Congratulations to Audra and the incredible Memorial High Choir Directors, Mr. Omar Samaniego and Ms. Kelly Lozano.”

post_text: Josiah Martinez, a student from McAllen High, is one of the top athletes in the nation in pole vaulting. He takes his studies seriously and like more than 22,000 other students in McAllen ISD, he has transitioned to distance learning. McAllen ISD students are utilizing distance learning to keep everyone safe during the COVID-19 crisis. His mother, Sarah Martinez, is a SPED teacher at Rayburn ES.

I’m looking forward to another great day of serving meals tomorrow.

post_text:
"While we would normally invite as many families as possible to take meals, we urge you to stay home unless you need a meal for your child or children."

Guidelines for McAllen ISD meals:

McAllen ISD cares about your health and well-being. Meals will be available from 11:30 a.m. – 12:30 p.m., Monday-Friday at either our Grab & Go sites or Meals on Wheels locations.

At Grab & Go sites, we prefer you remain in your vehicle and we will come to you.

At Meals on Wheels locations, please form a line and remain at least six-feet apart from those around you. You also have the option to remain in your vehicle.

Out of an abundance of caution, our staff will wear medical masks as a protective measure. A police officer will be at each site to help ensure everyone’s safety.

While we would normally invite as many families as possible to take meals, we urge you to stay home unless you need a meal for your child or children.

We appreciate everyone’s cooperation during this operation.

For a complete list of Grab & Go sites and Meals on Wheels locations, please click here: https://buff.ly/3bhROnN

post_text: Today’s training is a kick-off initiative to instill team collaboration, cohesiveness and a sense of higher purpose. We are motivating our transportation team to understand that part of their role is not only in academic achievement of our students, but caring for our students' overall social and mental well-being. Their role goes deeper than driving a school bus. It is about caring for our students. Our drivers have passion and love for the job that they do each day.

The McAllen ISD Book Club for employees will hold its first meeting at 5 p.m. on Tuesday, March 24, in the Texas Our Texas Room at the Staff Development Center located on the Achieve Early College High School campus (1601 N. 27th St.).

The Book Club’s first book, The Goldfinch by Donna Tartt, was picked by the McAllen Memorial High English Department and the next book will be picked by a different department. Surveys were sent to all grade levels in the District by Department Heads or Literacy Coaches. The book will be discussed at the March 24 meeting.

For questions or more information, contact Ms. Valeria Carpenter at valeria.carpenter@mcallenisd.net.

The McAllen ISD Book Club for employees will hold its first meeting at 5 p.m. on Tuesday, March 24, in the Texas Our Texas Room at the Staff Development Center located on the Achieve Early College High School campus (1601 N. 27th St.).

The Book Club’s first book, The Goldfinch by Donna Tartt, was picked by the McAllen Memorial High English Department and the next book will be picked by a different department. Surveys were sent to all grade levels in the District by Department Heads or Literacy Coaches. The book will be discussed at the March 24 meeting.

For questions or more information, contact Ms. Valeria Carpenter at valeria.carpenter@mcallenisd.net.

post_text: ICYMI: Watermill Express is a proud supporter of McAllen ISD schools. They sponsored an essay-writing contest for fourth graders. More than 1,000 students submitted essays and 10 winners were selected and honored on Dec. 12, 2019, at Perez Elementary. Students wrote essays where they created a super hero that would engage in healthy habits. The winners received a chrome laptop computer and wireless printer. The winners included Lily Faragoza (Roosevelt Elementary), Ian Gonzalez (Roosevelt), Lyric Menchaca (Fields Elementary), Nicholas Montes (Hendricks Elementary), Madalin Alcantar (Perez Elementary), Elizabeth Valdivia (Perez), Jessebella Gonzalez (Seguin Elementary), Leilani Mancillas (Sanchez Elementary), Sydney Acosta (Escandon Elementary) and Aryan Nair (Milam Elementary).

post_text: The public can donate new and unwrapped toys for the seventh annual Sara's Hope and Christmas Wishes Toy Drive. These donations are given to RGV children who are battling life threatening illness and will not be able to make it home for Christmas. There is a collection point in the band hall at McAllen Memorial High School (101 E. Hackberry Ave.). The deadline is Thursday, Dec. 19.

post_text:
The state has recognized McAllen ISD’s School Business Office for its financial transparency. The Texas Comptroller of Public Accounts has awarded McAllen ISD’s Business Services the Debt Obligations Star for exemplary efforts in creating financial transparency around public debt and the Transparency Star in the area of traditional finances for exemplary efforts in creating financial transparency around public services and spending decisions.

The Transparency Stars program recognizes local governments across Texas that strive to meet a high standard for financial transparency online. These efforts provide citizens with clear, consistent information about public spending in user-friendly formats. #DistrictOfChampions

post_text: McAllen Memorial High's Jacquelyn Douglas signed to compete in the discus at NCAA Division II Ashland University in Ohio. As a junior, she took seventh in the state last year in the discus. She was the champion in discus at the District, Area and Regional level. She broke the school discus record an incredible six times. Her personal best is 142-feet, 8 inches. #DistrictOfChampions #IChooseMcAllenISD

post_text: McAllen Memorial's Jacquelyn Douglas signed to compete in the discus at NCAA Division II Ashland University in Ohio on Wednesday. As a junior, she took seventh in the state last year in the discus. She was the champion in discus at the District, Area and Regional level. She broke the school discus record an incredible six times. Her personal best is 142-feet, 8 inches. Way to go!
